Thryve Labs, a spinout of Carnegie Foundry in collaboration with Carnegie Mellon University, will test its passive AI system to provide continuous environmental awareness. The system aims to streamline documentation, support evidence-based care plans, improve incident response, and enhance family communication—all while maintaining strict privacy controls, including local data storage and consent-based tracking.Barber National Institute Senior Vice President Robert Barber emphasized the importance of this innovation amid growing challenges in the caregiving sector, including high burnout rates and increasing demand for residential services. “If this technology can help reduce administrative tasks and give families greater transparency, it has the potential to expand our capacity without compromising personalized care,” Barber said.The pilot will actively involve staff feedback to ensure the technology supports, rather than replaces, direct support professionals. Both organizations stress that the goal is to enhance human expertise, not substitute it.Thryve Labs recently earned recognition through AI startup programs with AWS, Microsoft, Google, and NVIDIA, positioning the company to scale solutions that transform caregiving nationwide. Barber National Institute, which serves more than 5,400 individuals annually across Pennsylvania, continues to lead in integrating technology to strengthen its mission of inclusion and quality care.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
